of at least three books
for O'Reilly: Think Python, Think Stats, and

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:28.759
Think Complexity.

00:00:28.759 --> 00:00:36.490
Looking at an intersecting world of ideas
around, using software to explore other concepts.

00:00:36.490 --> 00:00:41.140
And he's a professor
at Olin College of Computer Science.

00:00:41.140 --> 00:00:47.970
A lot of us here at Google,
know him from his stint as a visiting scientist,

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:50.920
and Nathan Glasgow's
group Under Hiatus.

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:54.070
And just a quick personal anecdote.

00:00:54.070 --> 00:00:55.210
I took
this book home on Tuesday, by Wednesday afternoon,

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:56.210
there was already
an iterated prisoner's dilemma tournament

00:00:56.210 --> 00:01:02.930
going on in my house when I got home, so,
it's interesting, so thank you very much Allen.

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:05.869
&gt;&gt;Allen: Thank you very much David.

00:01:05.869 --> 00:01:07.610
Thank you all for coming.

00:01:07.610 --> 00:01:09.259
it's a lot of fun for me to be back.

00:01:09.259 --> 00:01:13.659
I was just pointing out
the part in the book that's about you.

00:01:13.659 --> 00:01:15.430
So enjoy that.

00:01:15.430 --> 00:01:19.360
If you want to follow along, that's the URL
for the slides I'm using.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:23.320
There are a few links in the slides, so if
you go to that, you'll be

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:26.600
able to follow those links.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:29.500
So as David mentioned,
when we were talking about this book, Think

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:31.140
Complexity,
I want to start out by telling you a little

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:34.409
bit of the history
of how this book came around.

00:01:34.409 --> 00:01:38.670
I teach at Olin College, which
is a small engineering college in Needham.

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:42.080
It's relatively new,
it's only been operating for about ten years.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:46.190
The mission of the college
is to create an innovative engineering program.

00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:50.330
And specifically for Computer Science,
we needed to create a curriculum

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:52.060
that made sense for engineers.

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:56.850
We don't offer a degree in Computer Science,
we offer degrees in engineering.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:02:02.229
Students can concentrate in Computer Science,
which is kind of like doing a minor,

00:02:02.229 --> 00:02:05.530
but we didn't want to just do an Engineering
major

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:06.530
with a C.S. minor.

00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:09.780
We thought that was an opportunity
to do something richer than that.

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:15.340
So what we weren't looking for is a Department
of Computer Science.

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:19.239
What we ended up doing is, taking the ideas
in Computer Science,

00:02:19.239 --> 00:02:21.991
took the whole curriculum,
and you can imagine if each class is a box,

00:02:21.991 --> 00:02:27.030
full of stuff, we just took all the stuff
and dumped it out on the table,

00:02:27.030 --> 00:02:30.379
threw away the boxes, and started rearranging
the stuff.

00:02:30.379 --> 00:02:36.180
'Cause a lot of the groupings of ideas are
historical,

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:38.879
and might not be the best choices for a current
curriculum.

00:02:38.879 --> 00:02:41.620
So, for example,
if you have the luxury of offering lots of

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.650
classes,
you'll have an Operating Systems class, a

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:47.239
Networking class,
and a Databases class,

00:02:47.239 --> 00:02:50.590
and there might not be explicit connections
between those.

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:52.110
But if you now take all those pieces,
and dump them on the table,

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:56.700
and say I'm going to teach one class that
covers those three topics,

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:58.900
well, you lose something,
because you're not going to be able

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:01.019
to cover everything that you did before.

00:03:01.019 --> 00:03:04.459
But you gain something because if you take
Operating Systems

00:03:04.459 --> 00:03:09.040
and Networks together, you're naturally talking
about Distributed Systems.

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:12.480
If you take File Systems and Databases together,
you're naturally

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:17.489
looking at a File System as a kind of Database,
or a Database as a kind of File System,

00:03:17.489 --> 00:03:20.900
and I think there are ideas that come out
of that.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:25.439
So we wrote about it, and we called it
"The Small Footprint Curriculum in Computer

00:03:25.439 --> 00:03:27.279
Science."

00:03:27.279 --> 00:03:30.459
The one problem that we found ourselves with
is

00:03:30.459 --> 00:03:35.719
that there was no natural place
to teach Data Structures.

00:03:35.719 --> 00:03:39.939
Now, this is a picture of my Ph.D. advisor,
Paul Hilfinger,

00:03:39.939 --> 00:03:43.629
who's been teaching Data Structures at Berkley,
for quite a long time,

00:03:43.629 --> 00:03:46.010
and I think he would be disappointed looking
at my curriculum

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:51.040
to see we weren't doing justice to Data Structures.

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:56.209
The problem that we ran into, was that
most of the way Data Structures gets taught

00:03:56.209 --> 00:03:57.859
is out its context.

00:03:57.859 --> 00:04:00.930
Kind of one Data Structure after another.

00:04:00.930 --> 00:04:04.890
Lots of pros and cons of this implementation
versus that implementation,

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:07.870
but mostly unmotivated.

00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:11.900
So that was stuck in my head,
okay, how are we going to get Data Structures

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:13.760
back
into the curriculum.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:19.590
At the same time, historically,
we had Complexity Science happening, and it's

00:04:19.590 --> 00:04:22.150
a little hard to characterize exactly what
was happening,

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:23.150
and when.

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:27.201
This is a time line from the Wikipedia page
on Complexity Science, that gives some of

00:04:27.201 --> 00:04:30.620
the timing
of the major events.

00:04:30.620 --> 00:04:36.750
The thing about this that was exciting
to me is that it's all relatively new.

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:42.620
You can study a whole lot of Math and Science
at the undergraduate level before you get

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:45.440
past,
say, the nineteenth century.

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:48.060
There's very little twentieth century math
and science

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:51.400
that you get to, until you get to grad school.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.660
But I thought there was an opportunity there
because Complexity Science, in addition to

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:57.690
being new,
is also very accessible.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:00.700
I'll talk in a minute
about ways that is accessible.

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:06.530
One of them is, there were lots of
popular nonfiction books written about Complexity.

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:09.900
So I started building a class around that.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:12.400
Version one of this class was in 2005.

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:18.190
And I started by just grabbing all the books
about this stuff, and trying to figure out

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:20.810
if we could find out what's there.

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:25.120
You know, there's a certain amount of hype,
is there some substance behind it?

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:30.590
And the other thing that I wanted to do was
start with the, start with the popular nonfiction,

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:32.870
which usually doesn't have the technical details
in it.

00:05:32.870 --> 00:05:33.870
There's no code.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:35.400
There's very little mathematics.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:39.800
But what you can do, in the context of a class,
is start with that, and dive in deeper.

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:42.090
So we found a number of the papers, the original
papers

00:05:42.090 --> 00:05:43.420
on these topics.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:46.330
Student re-implemented
a lot of the models that were described in

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:47.920
those papers.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:50.640
So that was the first version of the class.

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:52.990
At the end of the class,
I tried to summarize the whole thing

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:57.060
with what I call "the ultra-secret point of
the class."

00:05:57.060 --> 00:06:00.310
Because for the whole semester,
we didn't really know yet

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:03.240
what the class was about.

00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:05.770
I kind of did the same thing
the second time around.

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:10.490
I felt like I was playing "hide the football"
with the class for the whole semester.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:15.470
Because I hadn't, in my own head,
got to the point where I could explain

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:18.590
a coherent big picture of it was about.

00:06:18.590 --> 00:06:21.560
So I think we were having a good time,
we learned some more Python,

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:23.380
we got some more Data Structures.

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:27.090
We found ourselves talking
about philosophy of science quite a lot,

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:30.530
because the models that were coming up in
Complexity Science

00:06:30.530 --> 00:06:34.200
raised a lot of questions about
what exactly are we doing with these models?

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:39.680
What kind of science is this?" [phone rings]
That was the second iteration of the class.

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:47.550
The third iteration was just this past fall,
and I got to do a couple of things.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:49.420
One of them is, I wrote this book.

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:53.710
I had drafted parts of it,
but I finally sat down and wrote everything

00:06:53.710 --> 00:06:55.590
except chapter one.

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:59.620
We used that for the class,
and what the students did over the course

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:05.080
of the semester was, a set of case studies,
where they worked in teams of three or four.

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:08.550
And each of them chose a topic
that could have been a chapter in the book,

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:10.139
but wasn't.

00:07:10.139 --> 00:07:12.350
And they wrote the missing chapters of the
book

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:13.970
in the form of these case studies.

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:18.700
And some of them are now included in the book
that you've got.

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:22.389
So this, I thought, was a nice opportunity
to give the students a chance to do some authentic

00:07:22.389 --> 00:07:24.020
work
and get published.

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:26.990
In fact, I recruited a program committee to
get

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:30.220
other members of the faculty to do my grading
for me.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:35.870
So the students turned in their case studies,
I pretended I was the program chair,

00:07:35.870 --> 00:07:38.000
and sent out all the papers.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.530
The other faculty wrote reviews,
we decided which ones would be included;

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:43.670
which ones weren't quite ready.

00:07:43.670 --> 00:07:49.050
And then I edited in January,
and sent it to the publisher,

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:52.040
and O'Reilly I think does a really good job
of turning books around quickly.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:57.180
I turned in the manuscript in January,
and I think it was available in March.

00:07:57.180 --> 00:08:03.110
Which if you've worked with other publishers,
that's pretty remarkable.

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:06.490
And [claps hands softly]
in January, I finally sat down and wrote

00:08:06.490 --> 00:08:09.650
what I think is the "ultra secret point of
the book",

00:08:09.650 --> 00:08:12.770
which is the "ultra secret point of the class."

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:14.780
And I will now tell you what it is.

00:08:14.780 --> 00:08:18.230
Which is, I think,
the development of Complexity Science

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:22.060
has caused a quiet revolution in science.

00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:25.770
What I mean by that is,
what kind of activities do we mean when we

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:27.490
say "science."

00:08:27.490 --> 00:08:29.790
What do we think is a good theory?

00:08:29.790 --> 00:08:35.389
If you propose an explanation for something,
what's a satisfying explanation?

00:08:35.389 --> 00:08:40.300
And maybe hand in hand with that,
what's a good model of a physical system?

00:08:40.300 --> 00:08:44.620
I am going to talk about some of the
axes that I think we are moving along.

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:47.249
And I don't mean to say
that this is black and white.

00:08:47.249 --> 00:08:51.449
That it used to be a hundred percent this,
and now it's a hundred percent that,

00:08:51.449 --> 00:08:55.379
but that I think the center of mass
of scientific activity is gradually shifting

00:08:55.379 --> 00:09:00.420
from your point of view, from left to right,
on each of these axes.

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:03.079
From models of physical systems that tend
to be

00:09:03.079 --> 00:09:05.990
in the form of equations,
toward things that tend to be

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:07.920
in the form of simulation.

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:12.120
Away from mathematical analysis,
like symbolic computation,

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:16.329
and toward discrete computation.

00:09:16.329 --> 00:09:22.360
Continuous mathematics toward discrete mathematics;
linear models, linear systems, toward non-linear

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:23.360
models.

00:09:23.360 --> 00:09:24.800
I'll give an example of some of these in a
minute,

00:09:24.800 --> 00:09:29.820
I don't want to go too much into details,
but I talk about it more in the book.

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:34.259
Deterministic to stochastic,
I've also mentioned abstract and detailed

00:09:34.259 --> 00:09:35.730
in the context of modeling.

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:41.490
What I mean by that is a detailed model
is a realistic description of a physical system.

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:45.279
Where I can look at the physical system,
and the elements of my model,

00:09:45.279 --> 00:09:47.889
and there are clear analogs between them.

00:09:47.889 --> 00:09:51.790
I can match them up one to one,
and I can say "yep, that's a realistic description

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:53.220
of the system."

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:56.529
And when I say abstract, I mean mostly the
opposite of that.

00:09:56.529 --> 00:10:02.009
It’s a more, abstracted; it's a more, less
detailed description,

00:10:02.009 --> 00:10:04.209
less realistic.

00:10:04.209 --> 00:10:08.250
Some of the other axes,
if you are doing analysis, if you're doing

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:12.279
mathematical computation,
you tend to have to limit yourself to simple

00:10:12.279 --> 00:10:14.410
systems
that have a small number of components,

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:17.439
and those components are usually identical.

00:10:17.439 --> 00:10:19.399
With computational models,
you can often move

00:10:19.399 --> 00:10:25.379
toward large numbers of components,
that can be different, heterogeneous.

00:10:25.379 --> 00:10:28.040
Okay, that was pretty abstract.

00:10:28.040 --> 00:10:30.579
Let me give a more concrete example.

00:10:30.579 --> 00:10:36.600
So, celestial mechanics might be
the canonical example of classical science.

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:38.459
Which I'll just use the term of classical
science,

00:10:38.459 --> 00:10:40.949
just to contrast it with, whatever the new
thing is,

00:10:40.949 --> 00:10:43.129
maybe complexity science.

00:10:43.129 --> 00:10:46.470
So the question is, why are planetary orbits
elliptical?

00:10:46.470 --> 00:10:51.449
It's a natural kind of question to ask,
we'd like an explanation of that behavior.

00:10:51.449 --> 00:10:55.230
It turns out, if you know the law of Universal
Gravitation,

00:10:55.230 --> 00:11:00.000
you can write down a set of differential equations
that describes the motions of planets,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.700
at least for a simplified solar model, solar
system model.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:09.430
And if you now solve those differential equations,
you get ellipses, and you've explained

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:13.019
why those orbits are ellipses.

00:11:13.019 --> 00:11:16.399
And I think there's something very satisfying
about that kind of explanation.

00:11:16.399 --> 00:11:18.300
I think at least
most people find it satisfying.

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:25.889
I want to offer, as a point of comparison,
this is Thomas Schelling's model of racial

00:11:25.889 --> 00:11:26.889
segregation.

00:11:26.889 --> 00:11:29.800
Similarly, it is motivated by a "why" question.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:34.060
If you look at a lot of cities,
people are segregated by race, so you might

00:11:34.060 --> 00:11:35.420
ask "why?"

00:11:35.420 --> 00:11:40.399
What he proposed is a model
where the people in your city have two kinds,

00:11:40.399 --> 00:11:45.529
in this case, red and green,
and they all live on a two dimensional grid,

00:11:45.529 --> 00:11:50.680
so that each of them has eight neighbors,
and the model of their behavior

00:11:50.680 --> 00:11:55.569
is that they are happy
if at least a few of their neighbors are like

00:11:55.569 --> 00:11:56.569
themselves.

00:11:56.569 --> 00:12:00.399
So, if two or three out of the eight are the
same color,

00:12:00.399 --> 00:12:03.339
they're happy, and they stay put.

00:12:03.339 --> 00:12:08.670
If they have fewer neighbors like themselves,
they start to feel unhappy, and they move,

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:15.639
and moving in this case means just picking
a random, unoccupied cell in the grid,

00:12:15.639 --> 00:12:18.100
and moving to it, right?

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:23.089
So, you can characterize the agents,
in this model,

00:12:23.089 --> 00:12:25.610
as being mildly xenophobic.

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:29.149
They don't like
to be completely surrounded by people who

00:12:29.149 --> 00:12:32.339
are
not like themselves, but you probably wouldn't

00:12:32.339 --> 00:12:34.649
describe them as rabid racists.

00:12:34.649 --> 00:12:39.290
Nevertheless, the outcome of system tends
to look like what's happening on the right

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:45.079
there,
where things get almost completely segregated

00:12:45.079 --> 00:12:46.879
by color, in this case.

00:12:46.879 --> 00:12:50.379
And in fact, this is an intermediate step
in the process.

00:12:50.379 --> 00:12:54.889
If you keep running that,
it almost just becomes two great big blobs,

00:12:54.889 --> 00:12:58.600
with one boundary between them,
depending on the parameters

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:04.199
that you tweak in the system.

00:13:04.199 --> 00:13:06.699
The red and green,
anybody colorblind?

00:13:06.699 --> 00:13:08.689
Oh alright,
I just, I thought it funny that

00:13:08.689 --> 00:13:18.329
the people who made that particular,
graph, made it as inaccessible as possible.

00:13:18.329 --> 00:13:21.749
So the question is,
do you find the Newtonian explanation

00:13:21.749 --> 00:13:28.720
of elliptical orbits more satisfying
than the Schelling explanation of racial segregation?

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:33.459
I think most people do,
but I want to poke a little bit at why.

00:13:33.459 --> 00:13:36.499
There are a few characteristics of classical
science

00:13:36.499 --> 00:13:41.350
that make us feel good about it,
but it's not obvious that we are justified

00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:42.670
in feeling good.

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:45.459
So one of them is the appeal to a Universal
Law,

00:13:45.459 --> 00:13:49.310
in that case we were able to invoke
Universal Gravitation and I think there's

00:13:49.310 --> 00:13:51.569
something
about the fact that the same law

00:13:51.569 --> 00:13:58.149
applies to things moving on the Earth's surface,
and also to planets moving in solar systems,

00:13:58.149 --> 00:14:05.730
that makes us feel like that law has validity,
as opposed to a law that has very narrow scope.

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:07.079
Okay.

00:14:07.079 --> 00:14:10.959
There's a certain amount of mathematical virtuosity
that I think impresses us,

00:14:10.959 --> 00:14:13.749
and makes the work seem more real.

00:14:13.749 --> 00:14:16.220
I have a colleague in Physics that commonly
refers

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:19.930
to the sort of thing I do as
"playing with computers."

00:14:19.930 --> 00:14:25.059
So, mathematics is real, playing with computers
is fun and games.

00:14:25.059 --> 00:14:29.329
On the other hand I don't want to bias this
too much,

00:14:29.329 --> 00:14:31.199
I think that one might have been a little
bit edgy.

00:14:31.199 --> 00:14:37.269
But legitimately, predictive power is something
we would like to see in a model or a theory,

00:14:37.269 --> 00:14:43.410
and that was, is the great selling point
of Newton's explanation of Celestial Mechanics.

00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:48.060
We can predict solar eclipses, we can predict
all sort of things that are going to happen.

00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:52.939
That's not as true of Schelling's model.

00:14:52.939 --> 00:14:54.019
and "proofiness."

00:14:54.019 --> 00:14:57.040
It feels like we've just done
a mathematical proof.

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.869
Now, I would say, it's not a proof.

00:14:59.869 --> 00:15:03.329
We can't prove
a thing about actual physical systems.

00:15:03.329 --> 00:15:08.920
We can proove things about mathematical abstractions,
and we might hope that the proof

00:15:08.920 --> 00:15:14.040
about mathematical abstractions is analogous
to something in the real world, but that part's

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:16.870
just a hope.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:19.740
On the flip side, thinking about Schelling's
model,

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:22.170
the obvious characteristic of Schelling's
model

00:15:22.170 --> 00:15:26.519
is that you've just described human beings
by a set of rules,

00:15:26.519 --> 00:15:29.860
that says "I'm going to count the number
of my neighbors and be happy

00:15:29.860 --> 00:15:32.309
or unhappy depending on that count."

00:15:32.309 --> 00:15:36.579
Most sociologists would not be happy
with the reduction that you just made

00:15:36.579 --> 00:15:38.279
of human behavior.

00:15:38.279 --> 00:15:40.489
The other,
as I mentioned, is that you're just

00:15:40.489 --> 00:15:42.769
playing with computers.

00:15:42.769 --> 00:15:48.369
And the last is, if models like this
can't make detailed predictions,

00:15:48.369 --> 00:15:51.699
that allow us to validate whether
the model is correct or not,

00:15:51.699 --> 00:15:55.929
then what kind of work can they do?

00:15:55.929 --> 00:15:58.989
So this is the framework that I use
when I teach the class,

00:15:58.989 --> 00:16:02.839
and it appears in the book as well,
I think this is a general model

00:16:02.839 --> 00:16:07.049
of a lot of what we do when we
model the world, which describes

00:16:07.049 --> 00:16:09.889
scientific activity,
but I would also argue

00:16:09.889 --> 00:16:12.269
it describes how we think.

00:16:12.269 --> 00:16:17.449
Most of our thinking of the world
is in models like this where we have

00:16:17.449 --> 00:16:22.889
some physical system that we can observe,
we have either direct or indirect sensory

00:16:22.889 --> 00:16:24.869
data.

00:16:24.869 --> 00:16:30.079
We then construct a model,
sometimes implicitly, sometimes explicitly,

00:16:30.079 --> 00:16:35.209
that is an abstraction of the real thing,
meaning that we've left out details.

00:16:35.209 --> 00:16:38.619
The nice thing about the model though,
is that, unlike the real world,

00:16:38.619 --> 00:16:43.790
we can write proofs in models,
we can do analysis of models,

00:16:43.790 --> 00:16:45.989
we can run simulations of models.

00:16:45.989 --> 00:16:50.009
What you get out of that are predictions
and explanations that you can

00:16:50.009 --> 00:16:55.680
then compare to whatever it was that you saw
in the physical system, and get some

00:16:55.680 --> 00:17:00.149
kind of validation out of that.

00:17:00.149 --> 00:17:06.900
This is the framework
at least that I propose to my students.

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:12.000
And then we can ask, what kind of work
does Schelling's model do?

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.120
It's not a proof.

00:17:14.120 --> 00:17:15.670
It has very little predictive power.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:18.300
I can't tell you, I can't use Schelling's
model

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:23.170
to tell you how segregated Boston
will be in the future.

00:17:23.170 --> 00:17:27.020
But what it does provide is,
kind of a logical argument.

00:17:27.020 --> 00:17:30.450
It's an existence proof,
or a kind of counter example

00:17:30.450 --> 00:17:34.650
to the assumption
that if you see segregation in a city,

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:37.630
that the people who live there
must be racist.

00:17:37.630 --> 00:17:43.310
That the only explanation of segregation
is racist agents.

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:47.010
So the claim, I think,
that Schelling would make is that this

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:52.480
might be sufficient to cause segregation,
but it's not necessary.

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:56.810
You don't have to actually have people behaving
like this in order to see

00:17:56.810 --> 00:17:59.620
segregation as the outcome.

00:17:59.620 --> 00:18:01.830
And what that means is that
that segregation,

00:18:01.830 --> 00:18:07.840
the fact that city seems to be racist,
could be an emergent property.

00:18:07.840 --> 00:18:11.160
Meaning that the system as a whole has that
property,

00:18:11.160 --> 00:18:13.210
but the components do not.

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:19.530
The individual agents might not be racist.

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:23.010
I want to give one other example
of this kind of model, because I think

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:25.190
a couple of examples will help
us think about it.

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:28.400
I'm going to talk about
the Six Degrees experiment

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:30.530
that Stanley Milgram ran.

00:18:30.530 --> 00:18:32.790
How many people are familiar with Stanley
Milgram?

00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:37.400
Okay, if you're not,
I highly encourage you to find out more about

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:38.400
him.

00:18:38.400 --> 00:18:42.930
I think he's fascinating in part
because he ran two out of the three

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:47.270
most infamous experiments in all of social
science.

00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:49.370
One of them, that I just think you have to
read about

00:18:49.370 --> 00:18:53.140
if you haven't, is his study
of obedience to authority.

00:18:53.140 --> 00:18:58.500
This is the original, one of the original
deceptive, social behavior experiments

00:18:58.500 --> 00:19:02.180
where he brought people in,
and told them they were participating

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:07.760
in a teaching and learning experiment,
where they would act as a teacher,

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:10.570
and the "learner" on the other side of the
glass

00:19:10.570 --> 00:19:12.980
was actually an actor.

00:19:12.980 --> 00:19:17.730
And the subjects were told to administer
electric shocks whenever the "learner"

00:19:17.730 --> 00:19:19.860
got the answer wrong.

00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:22.930
And they would start out
by giving a fifteen volt shock,

00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:27.990
and work their way up a board,
to four hundred fifty volts.

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:30.950
And what would happen,
as you went from fifteen to four hundred fifty;

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:35.310
two things would happen:
one, the warning labels on the board,

00:19:35.310 --> 00:19:39.640
would say things like mild shock,
severe shock, hazard, warning, danger,

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:43.580
I don't remember exactly what it was,
but it was increasingly dramatic.

00:19:43.580 --> 00:19:47.000
Yellow and black, diamond and stripes,
everything.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:51.360
Also, the actor on the other side
of the glass, would go from saying things

00:19:51.360 --> 00:19:56.680
like "ow",
or "hey stop that" to "I'm having a heart

00:19:56.680 --> 00:20:03.040
attack, please stop!"
to silence [hesitant chuckles] at one point.

00:20:03.040 --> 00:20:08.540
The nature of the experiment was
to how far up the board people would be willing

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:10.660
to go under different circumstances.

00:20:10.660 --> 00:20:16.070
And, some of the circumstances, for example,
would be the "investigator" in a lab coat,

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:21.520
also an actor, standing behind the subject
and saying things like "You must continue,

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:25.250
the experiment requires you to continue."

00:20:25.250 --> 00:20:29.350
And you probably see where the punch line
of this is going, which is that many people

00:20:29.350 --> 00:20:33.240
will go much farther up the board
than you would like to believe about human

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:34.240
nature.

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:38.640
In fact, something like six--in some conditions,
I forget the exact details, something

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:41.760
like sixty percent of the subjects
went all the way to four hundred and fifty

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.200
volts,
and were asking for more.

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:45.200
And--

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:49.080
&gt;&gt; Male speaker 2: I think it was when
the authority assumed, said that they were

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:50.670
assuming all responsibility.

00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:52.011
&gt;&gt;Allen: Yeah, you're right.

00:20:52.011 --> 00:20:54.740
And there were
different scripts and different layouts

00:20:54.740 --> 00:21:00.090
of whether they could see the authority,
or whether they could see the learner, and

00:21:00.090 --> 00:21:01.330
so on.

00:21:01.330 --> 00:21:04.760
Fascinating stuff, especially because no one
will ever be allowed to run that experiment

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:05.760
again.

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:06.760
[laughter]

00:21:06.760 --> 00:21:09.550
&gt;&gt;Allen: Institutional review boards
were pretty much created,

00:21:09.550 --> 00:21:12.260
they should be called
the Stanley Milgram Memorial Institutional

00:21:12.260 --> 00:21:13.770
Review Boards.

00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:14.770
[laughter]

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:17.540
&gt;&gt;Allen: Anyway, fascinating stuff.

00:21:17.540 --> 00:21:19.140
Read
more about it if you're not already familiar

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:20.140
with it.

00:21:20.140 --> 00:21:22.900
The other experiment that he did, that is
the one that I'm

00:21:22.900 --> 00:21:26.300
going to talk a little bit about is
"The Small World" experiment, where he wanted

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:31.930
to investigate the structure of social networks
by seeing whether he could get a package delivered

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:36.150
across the country, following only social
hops.

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:41.570
So, I think he, they started in Wichita, Kansas,
and they had a couple of different targets,

00:21:41.570 --> 00:21:45.830
one of them was a stockbroker in Sharon, Massachusetts.

00:21:45.830 --> 00:21:50.540
My father was a stockbroker in Sharon, Massachusetts,
but not the target of the Milgram experiment.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:51.540
[laughter]

00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:56.130
&gt;&gt; Allen: The idea was that
Milgram, or one of his associates

00:21:56.130 --> 00:22:01.030
would give a package to someone and say, "I
want you to deliver this to

00:22:01.030 --> 00:22:06.980
this person" and they would be given
the name, occupation, and where they lived,

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:10.820
but the rules are you can only give this
to someone that you know personally.

00:22:10.820 --> 00:22:15.220
So, if you know the target personally,
you can just go give it to them, and you're

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:17.030
done,
and otherwise you have to give it to someone

00:22:17.030 --> 00:22:18.340
that you know personally.

00:22:18.340 --> 00:22:21.430
What he wanted to know was,
how many hops it would take to get from Wichita

00:22:21.430 --> 00:22:24.600
to Sharon, Massachusetts.

00:22:24.600 --> 00:22:30.730
And this graph shows the distribution
of hops for the packages that were delivered.

00:22:30.730 --> 00:22:35.000
Now, not all of the packages were delivered,
so there's a bias behind this, and that's

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.660
been the subject of a lot of discussion
but the interesting thing about this is

00:22:38.660 --> 00:22:41.040
that the mode is at six.

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:46.360
It took six hops
most often to get from source to destination,

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:50.340
and that's where the six degrees of separation
term

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:56.310
comes from, alright?

00:22:56.310 --> 00:23:00.730
So at the time, very little was known
about the structure of social networks,

00:23:00.730 --> 00:23:03.700
since then, it's been the subject of a lot
of study,

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:10.830
and we have several good explanations
of why the diameter of these social graphs

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:14.740
seems to be so much shorter than you would
expect.

00:23:14.740 --> 00:23:16.960
So that's the good thing that we have lots
of explanations.

00:23:16.960 --> 00:23:19.880
The bad thing is
we have too many explanations,

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:20.930
and they're incompatible.

00:23:20.930 --> 00:23:25.510
So, there are two models
that people have proposed

00:23:25.510 --> 00:23:30.740
simplified topologies that capture
important elements of social networks.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:35.580
Watts and Strogatz had what they
call a Small World Graph, which is a parameterized

00:23:35.580 --> 00:23:38.890
graph
between a completely regular graph on one

00:23:38.890 --> 00:23:41.400
end,
and a completely random graph on the other,

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:44.310
and what they find is a sweet spot in the
middle

00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:50.080
that behaves like social networks,
in the sense that it is highly clustered,

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:52.660
meaning that your friends tend to know each
other,

00:23:52.660 --> 00:23:57.700
but also has a small diameter,
meaning that it has this small world behavior.

00:23:57.700 --> 00:23:59.950
So that's one possible explanation.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:04.220
The other is Barabasi and Albert's model,
which is a scale free network.

00:24:04.220 --> 00:24:07.130
The way you build one of these is
by growing it.

00:24:07.130 --> 00:24:10.200
So if you start out with one,
or a small number of nodes,

00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:14.850
and gradually add nodes,
with the property of preferential attachment,

00:24:14.850 --> 00:24:19.120
meaning the rich get richer,
and/or don't go as fast,

00:24:19.120 --> 00:24:25.350
what you get is a high,
a long tailed distribution of degree

00:24:25.350 --> 00:24:27.130
in the network.

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:29.520
Most people have
a small number of friends,

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:33.270
but there are a few people
who have a very large number of friends.

00:24:33.270 --> 00:24:38.330
That graph also has the Small World Property,
and so now, if you're trying to explain

00:24:38.330 --> 00:24:44.580
the Small World Property,
you don't know which explanation is right.

00:24:44.580 --> 00:24:48.730
This is part of the reason
in my class that I found myself inevitably

00:24:48.730 --> 00:24:51.900
talking
about philosophy of science,

00:24:51.900 --> 00:24:56.890
because we just left the world of doing science,
building models,

00:24:56.890 --> 00:24:59.390
and using them to predict, explain and design.

00:24:59.390 --> 00:25:02.350
What we're now talking about is
theory choice.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:04.940
Why should I
prefer one model, or theory,

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:06.360
over another?

00:25:06.360 --> 00:25:12.150
And so that led us to Thomas Kuhn,
who wrote The Structure of Scientific Revolutions,

00:25:12.150 --> 00:25:14.380
which is probably his most famous book.

00:25:14.380 --> 00:25:17.930
If you're not familiar with that book in particular,
you're almost certainly familiar with

00:25:17.930 --> 00:25:19.060
Paradigm Shifts.

00:25:19.060 --> 00:25:21.090
That book introduced
that term.

00:25:21.090 --> 00:25:25.290
So all the bad jokes
about paradigm shifts that we've had

00:25:25.290 --> 00:25:30.650
for the last, let's see,
since 1963 or 4.

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:32.220
You can
blame Thomas Kuhn for that

00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:34.910
particular piece of vocabulary.

00:25:34.910 --> 00:25:38.960
He also wrote an essay called
"Objectivity, Value Judgment, and Theory Choice"

00:25:38.960 --> 00:25:43.470
which is explicitly about the situation
we were just talking about.

00:25:43.470 --> 00:25:47.640
Two competing models,
in some sense they both explain the data,

00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:52.810
so you can't choose one over the other
purely in terms of how well it fits data.

00:25:52.810 --> 00:25:56.780
There have to be other criteria,
and that's exactly what he explains.

00:25:56.780 --> 00:25:59.580
Well, what are those other criteria?

00:25:59.580 --> 00:26:04.270
Both descriptively,
like if we watch scientists

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:07.430
and listen to what they say,
what are the criteria that they seem

00:26:07.430 --> 00:26:09.070
to be applying?

00:26:09.070 --> 00:26:12.290
And also normatively, which is,
which of those criteria do we think

00:26:12.290 --> 00:26:14.090
are justified?

00:26:14.090 --> 00:26:18.690
And which might be biased?

00:26:18.690 --> 00:26:22.660
One of the reasons that the class
inevitably ends up in philosophy was...

00:26:22.660 --> 00:26:28.030
explained nicely by xkcd, which found
that the structure of information,

00:26:28.030 --> 00:26:33.520
at least as represented by Wikipedia,
has a tendency to lead inevitably to philosophy.

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:36.830
And this came out by the experiment
that if you take any article,

00:26:36.830 --> 00:26:39.810
and click on the first link,
and repeat that process,

00:26:39.810 --> 00:26:43.620
you will eventually end up at "Philosophy."
if you haven't read that cartoon,

00:26:43.620 --> 00:26:50.410
I recommend it to you.

00:26:50.410 --> 00:26:53.560
so I took some of the things
that we were talking about in the class,

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:56.440
and made them into a running theme throughout
the book.

00:26:56.440 --> 00:27:00.990
So each chapter tends to raise a different
issue

00:27:00.990 --> 00:27:02.650
in philosophy of science, and then I tried
to

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:06.320
write a little bit about it, just enough
to introduce what I thought were interesting

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:10.470
questions
and hopefully point you to toward more reading.

00:27:10.470 --> 00:27:12.680
I mentioned Theory Choice as one of the first
topics

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:13.730
that comes up.

00:27:13.730 --> 00:27:16.400
The Demarcation problem is one of the others.

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:20.950
The Demarcation problem is, is there a justified
definition

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:24.160
of science that lets us distinguish between
things

00:27:24.160 --> 00:27:29.660
that are real science, good science,
and other things like pseudo-science, or,

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:32.850
that
seem that like they might be sciencey, but

00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:34.010
they're not?

00:27:34.010 --> 00:27:36.770
Or say, religion, things that are not science
at all,

00:27:36.770 --> 00:27:42.080
but how do we clearly, justify that definition?

00:27:42.080 --> 00:27:44.740
Realism and instrumentalism comes up quite
a lot.

00:27:44.740 --> 00:27:50.110
This is, this pertains to how we interpret
the theories and models that we're using

00:27:50.110 --> 00:27:52.460
to describe physical systems.

00:27:52.460 --> 00:27:54.370
I won't say too much
about that now, I'm going to come back to

00:27:54.370 --> 00:27:56.080
it
just a little bit later.

00:27:56.080 --> 00:27:59.460
Holism and reductionism was one of the other
topics

00:27:59.460 --> 00:28:00.460
that comes up.

00:28:00.460 --> 00:28:05.400
Again I won't say too much about that
right now.

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:09.880
But I will come back to as I said,
the ultra secret point of this book.

00:28:09.880 --> 00:28:15.070
I started with this set of axes,
at the beginning,

00:28:15.070 --> 00:28:21.530
and I speculate, or at least my thesis
that we are living through a transition

00:28:21.530 --> 00:28:23.580
toward a new kind of science.

00:28:23.580 --> 00:28:27.060
I'm kind of borrowing that phrase
from Steven Wolfram,

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:29.650
but I mean it in a different sense then he
does.

00:28:29.650 --> 00:28:33.650
So, I'm going to have to violate
his trademark on that phrase.

00:28:33.650 --> 00:28:38.920
He is primarily talking about, well,
actually tell you what, if you want

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:41.780
to know what Wolfram is saying
when he says new kind of science,

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:44.340
ask me after, let's not go down that.

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:46.890
What I mean by it is just
what I was saying before,

00:28:46.890 --> 00:28:51.410
the shift along these axes
in what we think is science; what we think

00:28:51.410 --> 00:28:55.260
is a good model; what we think
is a satisfying kind of explanation; what

00:28:55.260 --> 00:28:59.780
we think is good work for a scientist to do.

00:28:59.780 --> 00:29:03.570
I think there are some other shifts going
on at the same time

00:29:03.570 --> 00:29:04.850
that are related.

00:29:04.850 --> 00:29:10.840
One of them is what kind of work
do we want models to do?

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:14.200
With the Newton example,
and the Schelling example, I wanted to show

00:29:14.200 --> 00:29:19.250
what I think is a shift for models that are
primarily meant to be predictive.

00:29:19.250 --> 00:29:23.260
They were often
tools that we would use as computational devices,

00:29:23.260 --> 00:29:26.490
for making predictions that had practical
consequences.

00:29:26.490 --> 00:29:30.620
I think there's a shift toward models
that may be explanatory without necessarily

00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:32.970
having predictive property.

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:36.400
I mentioned realism and instrumentalism,
alright, let me finally say what I mean by

00:29:36.400 --> 00:29:37.400
that.

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:41.440
Let me throw out an idea.

00:29:41.440 --> 00:29:43.760
Are electrons real?

00:29:43.760 --> 00:29:48.400
By a common language use of the word real?

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:51.120
Alright, so I think we would all buy, or at
least

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:54.400
I'll ask you to accept, that chair is real.

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:55.400
Okay?

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:57.510
Unicorns are not real.

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:03.380
So on that axis of real/not real,
[laughter] what's your feeling about electrons?

00:30:03.380 --> 00:30:08.000
&gt;&gt;male speaker 2: Not real.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:09.000
