00:52:36.060 --> 00:52:38.810
as part of your paradigm shift?

00:52:38.810 --> 00:52:40.190
&gt;&gt;Allen: Right, Okay.

00:52:40.190 --> 00:52:44.970
So I think, so the Xeno example
is one of those cases where

00:52:44.970 --> 00:52:50.500
the two endpoints are clear, and, but something
must change in the middle, but we have a really

00:52:50.500 --> 00:52:52.930
hard time saying where it changed in the middle,
and I think

00:52:52.930 --> 00:52:57.160
realism and instrumentalism has that character
as well.

00:52:57.160 --> 00:53:02.550
There are some examples where the vast majority
of us feel entirely comfortable saying,

00:53:02.550 --> 00:53:04.550
"Yup, that's real."

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:07.390
At the other end
of the spectrum, things that we all, at least

00:53:07.390 --> 00:53:10.820
have a consensus,
that they're not, something in the middle,

00:53:10.820 --> 00:53:12.920
there has
to be a transition somewhere in the middle.

00:53:12.920 --> 00:53:14.760
Where do we put it?

00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:26.240
One way to resolve that is to say,
is to accept as real, any entity postulated

00:53:26.240 --> 00:53:29.580
by a theory that we use.

00:53:29.580 --> 00:53:32.599
So if it's a good theory,
then the entities that it postulates are real.

00:53:32.599 --> 00:53:37.020
In other words, you just expand the space
of what you're willing to call real,

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:39.000
to make the conflict go away.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:41.800
The other is
to go all the way to instrumentalism,

00:53:41.800 --> 00:53:48.410
and say that all of our theories are tools
that we use to explain stuff, and we're not

00:53:48.410 --> 00:53:51.980
obligated
to consider any of our hypostulated entities

00:53:51.980 --> 00:53:53.460
as real.

00:53:53.460 --> 00:53:59.240
Even things that seem even obviously real,
like nice firm objects,

00:53:59.240 --> 00:54:04.050
which at the Mezzo scale of physics, have
nice reality to them,

00:54:04.050 --> 00:54:09.840
but if you go to very small scales, that starts
to get fuzzy.

00:54:09.840 --> 00:54:12.400
Now with nice solid objects, I think we have
a hard time with it.

00:54:12.400 --> 00:54:15.210
One of the examples I like to use is mushrooms.

00:54:15.210 --> 00:54:18.210
When when you look at a mushroom, what you're
actually

00:54:18.210 --> 00:54:22.380
looking at is this fruiting body of a fungus.

00:54:22.380 --> 00:54:25.660
And that thing
that's discrete and we pick up and eat, seems

00:54:25.660 --> 00:54:28.360
to have nice
realness to it.

00:54:28.360 --> 00:54:36.510
But that organism, that you just harvested,
is actually a very fine network of cells that

00:54:36.510 --> 00:54:38.190
is mostly underground.

00:54:38.190 --> 00:54:41.400
The underground part might be hundreds or
thousands, or millions of times

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:44.750
more massive than the thing you just picked
up.

00:54:44.750 --> 00:54:49.859
So in the sense of being big,
and concrete, it's real, but it's also

00:54:49.859 --> 00:54:52.450
really diffuse.

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:54.630
It doesn't have borders that can track.

00:54:54.630 --> 00:54:58.690
You couldn't dig it up,
you would end up digging up an acre of land.

00:54:58.690 --> 00:55:03.190
And you couldn't separate it from the soil
that it's part of, so it has some of the characteristics

00:55:03.190 --> 00:55:07.140
that we associate with nice, concrete, well
delineated objects,

00:55:07.140 --> 00:55:08.530
but not all of them.

00:55:08.530 --> 00:55:12.970
That's one of those
weird middle test cases, that I like to think

00:55:12.970 --> 00:55:14.260
about.

